In the following, we use intensity-dependent EQE measurements to experimentally quantify the QE loss caused by trap-assisted recombination in the bulk. For this purpose, we conduct IPC measurements under short-circuit conditions at an excitation wavelength of 520 nm. The associated two-step EQE behavior is distinctly different to that observed for other first-order loss mechanisms (e.g., of CT states and excitons) which are expected to be independent of light intensity. Thus, the presence of such a two-step EQE can be used to unambiguously identify trap-assisted recombination in organic photovoltaics devices. We note that to experimentally detect first-order recombination via trap states, the photocurrent needs to be recorded over a broad intensity range and at extremely low modulation frequencies (f\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
